<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of turnover tax in the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Preface</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the audit offices are empowered to examine the whole of public finances.</seg>
<seg id="4">The declaration requires the courts to have the power to examine tax collection as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The organisation of the European Supreme Audit Bodies (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The thematic focus of VI. EuroSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, formed the audit of public revenue by the Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="7">One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activities of a Court of Auditors is the development of a special strategy for auditing public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="8">This is particularly true of taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.</seg>
<seg id="9">As the national economies are increasingly interdependent and interdependent, there can be a situation in which the national audit offices can only carry out their audit activities in cooperation with the audit offices of other countries.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example can be the examination of internationally organized fraud, which can lead to significant losses of revenue in many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Cooperation between authorities is needed in the fight against such crimes.</seg>
<seg id="12">Audit bodies in this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">The idea of examining turnover tax and the MIAS system is in the VI. EuroSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Court.</seg>
<seg id="14">In the course of thorough preparation, the auditors involved first had to familiarise themselves with the legal framework and procedures for the management of turnover tax in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">On the basis of the analysis of the available information, we carried out the selection of subjects for examination planning.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving the efficient and effective management of turnover tax is a long-standing problem and individual Member States (particularly the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of turnover tax and create greater transparency in this area.</seg>
<seg id="17">We are convinced that the results of our audit can contribute not only to improving the work of the financial management, but also provide the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of turnover tax in the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Reference number: CZ) 06 / 27 (EN) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Basis of assessment:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Administration of turnover tax following the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(De) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004</seg>
<seg id="24">The Commission's audit objective is:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The purpose of the examination in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the financial authorities in the field of turnover tax following the integration of the Czech Republic into the single market in the European Community (hereinafter referred to).</seg>
<seg id="26">(De) The purpose of the investigation was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control, focusing on mutual assistance in the field of turnover tax in accordance with the abovementioned Regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations should be made to remedy them.</seg>
<seg id="28">VAT information exchange system The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Court of Auditors (Brh) of the Federal Republic of Germany on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The main areas of cooperation were the review of selected business events between entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international mutual assistance between tax administrations and the comparison of VAT management systems in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">A joint final report on the results of the audits was drawn up in accordance with European Guideline No 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The period audited covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of the parallel examination</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel audit of the turnover tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two audit offices.</seg>
<seg id="34">In addition to the focus on "exchange of information" under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925 / 2004, other closely related aspects have also been examined, such as the registration of tax</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation with regard to international passenger transport by coach and bus and the comparison of statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">In comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two countries, differences were noted in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) Registration for the purposes of turnover tax.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among other things, the main criterion for registration is that the turnover threshold laid down in the turnover tax law is exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, taxable persons receive only a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.</seg>
